### Description

Angular decorators are pretty verbose, specially with @Component. Maybe some simplified overload and convetnions could help.

### Proposed solution

````ts
ComponentDecorator {
	// current
	(args: any[]): any 
	
	// proposal
	(selector: string, templateUrl: string): any
	(selector: string, templateUrl: string, ...styleUrls: string[]): any
}

@Component("my", "my.component.html") // new
@Component({ selector: 'my', templateUrl: 'my.component.html' }) // old

@Component("my", "my.component.html", "my.component.css", "other.css") // new
@Component({ selector: 'my', templateUrl: 'my.component.html', styleUrls: ["my.component.css", "other.css"] }) // old
````


### Alternatives considered

An extended version could use also convention inference based in component.ts filename

````ts
ComponentDecorator {
	// current
	(args: any[]): any 
	
	// proposal
	(selector: string, inferCssUrl?: boolean): any
	(selector: string, templateUrl: string): any
	(selector: string, templateUrl: string, styleUrl: string): any
	
	// extended proposal
	(selector: string, inferCssUrl: boolean): any
}

@Component('my') // new (it infers templateUrl be convetion)
@Component({ selector: 'my', templateUrl: 'my.component.html' }) // old

@Component('my', true) // new (it also infers styleUrl by convetion)
@Component({ selector: 'my', templateUrl: 'my.component.html', styleUrls: ['my.component.css'] }) // old
````

